    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="846"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d846">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12637.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Vice
                        Consul <persName type="to">Silliman</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 28, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Brazilian Minister, Mexico City, telegraphed last night that Carbajal
                    delegates had just left for Vera Cruz, whence they will <pb facs="0690" n="574"
                        xml:id="pg_574"/> proceed to Tampico, with instructions to negotiate at any
                    convenient place. The change in itinerary was adopted owing to a break in the
                    railway near San Luis Potosí.</p>
                <p>Bring the above to the attention of General Carranza and ask him to issue orders
                    to Tampico authorities looking to protection and comfort of delegates and their
                    prompt meeting with Constitutionalist delegates. Telegraph names of
                    Constitutionalist delegates as soon as possible.</p>
                <p>Again express to Carranza this Government’s hope that no effort will be spared to
                    secure an immediate armistice, and again urge upon him the importance of
                    arranging a comprehensive amnesty and suitable guaranties.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
